title: For Sale:  Steyr AUG A3 by Sabre Defense Ind.
postcontent:
I am selling my Steyr AUG A3 rifle. It has a full 16" barrel and is chambered in .223. This rifle will include (5) 30 round mags, (3) 40 round mags, and a factory STEYR soft case to put everything in.


A little history,
This Aug A3 was made by Sabre Defense Industries from late 2008 until October of 2010 from parts kits made by Steyr in Austria and imported into the United States. There were approximately 3000 AUG A3's made by Sabre starting with serial number 1USAXXX all the way up to a possible 1USA999, then started 2USA001 and so on. In 2010 Sabre got into legal trouble with the ATF which resulted in a raid and seizure of all the remaining parts kits, they were sent back to Steyr. Long story short in August of 2012 Sabre started making A3's again starting with 3USAXXX but this time with the famous Tulip flash hiders. 3USAXXX is where Sabre ends their time with the A3. Number set 4USAXXX is when Vltor got the contract from Steyr and started making the Aug A3's and I think they are still making them today. This Aug I am selling is a low serial number, was made by Sabre and it is number 1USA532. so the 532nd AUG A3 ever made. I thought that was pretty cool, anyways here it is for sale.

I will attach a picture below of the 1USAXXX A3 rifle since the 2 and 3 number sets are different. If you have any questions feel free to email me and thank you for looking.

title: Want To Buy:  WTB 22LR ammo in quantity
postcontent:
I am still looking to buy a large quantity (up to a couple cases - 5,000-10,000 rounds) of 22 LR ammo.  I won't lie - I am not a Boy Scout troop, church camp etc., and I am not going to feed hungry kids or teach gun haters the joys of shooting.  I am also not asking for charity.  I am fine with you profiting reasonably on you scarce commodity to save me the hassle of scrounging for a little bit at a time going from store to store.
All of that said, prices are trending downward so I'm not looking to pay $50+ per brick or $.10 per round for cheap bulk ammo.  I don't want to drive all over the Metro Detroit area for a brick at a time either.  I am located in north Oakland county.  How far I'm willing to drive depends on the quantity, price and quality of your ammo.  
I have cash ready to go.  I will show up when we agree, where we agree and conduct a simple easy transaction.  If you've sold much through armslist, you know that is much less common than it should be - there are a lot of wishy-washy people out there.  I won't waste your time if you don't waste mine.
What do I mean by waste my time?
I will determine the seriousness of your offer by your ability to write in complete sentences telling me 
 - what exactly you're selling (how much of what brand and type) 
 - how much you want 
 - and where you are located or want to meet
I have found that those who can accomplish those simple things generally complete a deal in a business like manner and those who can't usually don't.

title: For Sale:  Henry Rifle 45/70
postcontent:
Introduced by the U.S. Army in 1873, this cartridge was first known as the .45 Government. As it made its way into commercially produced firearms the name .45-70 appeared, because it was loaded with a 70 grain blackpowder charge with 405 and 500 grain bullets. Virtually all rifle making companies of the late 19th century chambered their single shots and lever actions for the .45-70. As those companies and their rifles faded away, the .45-70's popularity did not. Factory .45-70 ammunition has been cataloged continuously since 1873 but never in the variety of loadings available now, in the 21st century. They range from 405 grain lead bullet, low-velocity loads for deer hunting and target shooting to high-velocity 300 to 400 grain jacketed bullet ones meant for large game.

Our new Model H010 .45-70 can handle them all. Its receiver is blued steel fitted with an 18.43" round barrel underneath and a tubular magazine of four-round capacity. Its pistol-grip buttstock and steel-capped forend are crafted of beautiful American walnut and cut with checkering to provide a sure grip. The buttstock wears a soft rubber pad to help shooters handle .45-70 recoil from a 7.08 lb. rifle. The model H010 will be factory issued with XS Ghost Ring rear peep sight with blade front. Because the receiver is drilled and tapped, scope mounting is an easy option.

If you need a handy yet powerful lever gun capable of fast repeat shots in the bear country of Alaska, or just a short, light rifle for deer hunting in the mountains of Pennsylvania, our new Model H010 will provide the accuracy and reliability you can count on.
